[2] Ukraine
-----------
Date: Mon 31 Oct 2011
Source: ForUm [edited]
http://en.for-ua.com/news/2011/10/31/115840.html


The Health Ministry of Ukraine has declared that the level of measles
morbidity does not exceed the epidemic threshold, but it is better to
be ready for an outbreak. The WHO representative in Ukraine, Igor
Pokanevych, stated that as of 20 Sep 2011, 40 of 53 Member States in
the WHO European Region have reported 26 025 confirmed measles cases
for the period January - July 2011.

The highest number of cases was reported from France, with 14 025
cases for the 1st 6 months of the year [2011]. In addition, 11 of all
cases in the Region were fatal (6 in France and one in each in
Germany, Kyrgyzstan, Romania, the Former Yugoslav Republic of
Macedonia and the United Kingdom). The most recent outbreak was
reported from Israel in September 2011, with 12 cases. According to
Pokanevych, [in North America], the largest outbreak was in Quebec,
Canada, involving 742 cases. In contrast, 213 cases were registered in
the United States. Most of these outbreaks are linked to importations
from Europe.

Pokanevych noted that in 2012, Ukraine is hosting the Euro football
championship and called upon the authorities to conduct an information
campaign and [enhance] immunization. In his turn, the representative
of the Sanitary Epidemic Agency of the Health Ministry, Viktor Svita,
stated that there were 194 cases of measles registered in Ukraine in
2011, and 93 percent of them were in the territory of the Western
Ukraine. He pointed out that Ukraine has a problem with vaccination
and revaccination. "The number of unvaccinated children increases,"
Svita added.

The Chief infection disease doctor of the Health Ministry, Kramariv,
underlined that adults are at greater risk from the measles outbreak
than children. He also noted that adults can voluntarily get
vaccinated, and as for children, there is a vaccination calendar,
according to which Ukrainian children are vaccinated free of charge.

