[5] New Zealand (Otago)
Date: Mon 31 Oct 2011
Source: stuff.co.nz [edited]
http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/5886184/Fears-of-measles-outbreak-in-Otago


A Dunedin Hospital staff member has been diagnosed with measles,
raising fears the outbreak of the disease has spread to the region.
The woman was the 2nd person to have contracted measles in Otago, with
both cases linked to a visitor from Wellington. There is currently an
outbreak of measles in New Zealand, with 373 cases this year [2011],
with the majority, 295, in Auckland.

The Southern District Health Board (DHB) said the infected woman had
contact with patients and other staff members at the early stages of
the illness last Monday [24 Oct 2011]. She then travelled to Auckland
on Tuesday and returned on Friday [25 and 28 Oct 2011]. The DHB said
they were making "every effort" to alert people who had come into
contact with her. Air New Zealand had provided passenger seating
lists, and people seated in the same row, 2 rows in front and a row
behind her were being contacted. Close contacts who were not immunised
against measles have been isolated for 14 days to prevent potential
spread of the disease.

The DHB's medical officer of health, Derek Bell, said there were
countless opportunities for other people to have been exposed because
measles is so easily transmitted. He said the only way to prevent
measles is by vaccination, or by having had the disease in the past.
"Parents should ensure that children are vaccinated on time, according
to the Childhood Immunisation Schedule. This involves MMR (measles,
mumps and rubella) vaccination at 15 months and 4 years. If there is a
community outbreak, there may be a recommendation for these childhood
vaccinations to be moved forward. Adults who were born before 1969 are
presumed to be immune to measles. Adults born after 1969 should check
that they have had 2 doses of measles vaccine. Many will have only had
one dose, and a 2nd dose is funded by the immunisation benefit," Bell
said.

