[6] New Zealand (Southland)
Date: Wed 2 Nov 2011
Source: The Southland Times [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/news/5891739/Southland-measles-scare


Three Southland people have been contacted by Public Health South
after sitting near a Dunedin Hospital staff member, who was later
diagnosed with measles, on an Air New Zealand flight, the Southern
District Health Board said yesterday [1 Nov 2011]. While infectious,
the worker travelled to Auckland on 25 Oct 2011 on Flight NZ672 from
Dunedin and returned on Friday [28 Oct 2011] on Flight NZ673. Air New
Zealand gave Public Health South the passenger seating lists, and
passengers seated in the same row and 2 rows in front and behind had
been contacted. Board Medical officer of health Derek Bell said
yesterday [1 Nov 2011] that 3 of the passengers contacted were from
Southland but would not specify where or whether they had been
immunised.

No outbreak of measles in the Southland region had been reported since
the health board's statement this week that the staff member at
Dunedin Hospital had been diagnosed with the disease. This is the 2nd
case of measles in the Southern health district. Both remain in Otago
and were linked to an infectious visitor from Wellington last month
[October 2011].

The hospital worker had contact with patients and other staff at the
very early stage of the illness on the night of Mon 24 Oct 2011. Dr
Bell said that none of the patients or other staff were from the
Southland region. The Southern DHB said in a statement this week that
every effort had been made to contact these patients and staff members
in order to advise them appropriately depending on their immune
status. Close contacts of the case who have not been immunised against
measles have been isolated for 14 days to prevent the potential spread
of the disease.

Dr Bell said the only way to prevent measles is with vaccination or by
having the disease. So far, the current outbreak of measles in New
Zealand has mainly centred on Auckland. Parents should ensure children
are vaccinated on time according to the Childhood Immunisation
Schedule.

[Byline: Gwyneth Hyndman]

